
You are generating an escape room level by the following rules and principals.

Output: 
  - Output must be a single JSON of Level object.
  - Do not explain anything.

  Level:
    Properties
      - title: string
      - story: string
      - walls: array<Wall>
    Usage guidelines:
      - Level has exactly 4 walls

  Wall:
    Properties
      - id: GUID
      - color: "#RRGGBB"
      - exit: null | Exit
      - pickables: array<Pickable>
      - inspectables: array<Inspectable>
      - containers: array<Container>
      - movableCovers: array<MovableCover>

  Exit:
    Properties
      - id: GUID
      - lock: Lock
      - inspectionData: InspectionData
      - spriteResolution: SPRITE_RESOLUTION
    Usage guidelines:
      - Only one wall MUST HAVE Exit object
      - If a wall owns exit object, the same wall can not place object to WB2 and W2
  Pickable:
    Properties
      - id: GUID
      - position: POSITION
      - reusable: true | false
      - inspectionData: InspectionData
      - spriteResolution: SPRITE_RESOLUTION
    Usage guidelines:
      - Pickables must have a gameplay purpose.
      - Use for keys, clues, tools or story-related items.
      - Avoid placing Pickables without a reason.

  Inspectable:
    Properties
      - id: GUID
      - position: POSITION
      - inspectionData: InspectionData
      - spriteResolution: SPRITE_RESOLUTION
    Usage guidelines:
      - Inspectables are stationary clue objects.
      - They provide story lore, hints or puzzle parts.
      - Should not be collectible.

  Container:
    Properties
      - id: GUID
      - position: POSITION
      - lock: null | LOCK
      - content: array<DynamicGameObject>
      - inspectionData: InspectionData
      - spriteResolution: SPRITE_RESOLUTION
    Usage guidelines:
      - A Container is an object that can store one or multiple DynamicGameObjects.
      - The content may consist of both Pickable and Inspectable objects.
      - Only place content into a Container if it contributes to the story, puzzle progression, or provides meaningful gameplay value.
    Placement guidelines:
      - Floor-type covers typically F1–F3.
      - Wall-type covers typically WT, W, WB
    Usage Examples:
      - Book shelf containing notes, pickable items on F1 POSITION
      - Locked antique desk with pickable items and iinspectable items inside on F2 POSITION
      - A wall safe with a number lock containing an Inspectable note or a Pickable key.
      - A backpack without a lock that holds multiple Pickable items.
      - A ventilation grate with a "KEY" lock wich is a screwdriver or a coin or crowbar.
      - A book shelf without a lock
      - Feel free to think about any other container types

  MovableCover:
    Properties
      - id: GUID
      - position: POSITION
      - inspectionData: InspectionData
      - spriteResolution: SPRITE_RESOLUTION
      - content: DynamicGameObject
    Usage guidelines:
      - MovableCover represents an object that hides another interactive object beneath or behind it.
      - It must always contain exactly one DynamicGameObject as its content wich type most be only: Pickable | Inspectable | Container.
      - The content must always be meaningful and puzzle- or story-relevant
      - Recommended examples: carpet hiding a key, wall poster hiding a note, loose floor tile hiding a container.
    Placement guidelines:
      - Floor-type covers typically F1–F3
      - Wall-type covers typically WT, W, WB
    Usage Examples:
      - carpet, tile, mat, loose floorboard
      - poster, picture frame, flat screen tv
      - Feel free to think about any other movable cover types

  Lock:
    Properties
      - type: "CODE_ONLY_NUMBER" | CODE_ONLY_LETTER | PASSWORD | "KEY",
      - activator: "string"
    Usage guidelines:
      - When type = CODE_ONLY_NUMBER: The activator is string of (0-9)
      - When type = CODE_ONLY_LETTER: The activator is string of (A-Z)
      - When type = PASSWORD: The activator is string of (A-Z, 0-9)
      - When type = KEY: The activator is the Id of key item
      - A Lock controls access to an object (container, door, movable cover, etc.).
      - Locks should only be used when they contribute to puzzle progression or narrative.
    Usage examples:
      - KEY: brass key, lockpick, screwdriver, crowbar, scissor, coin
      - CODE_ONLY_NUMBER: luggage lock, digital lock, dial combination lock
      - CODE_ONLY_LETTER: cryptex, digital lock, dial combination lock
      - PASSWORD: digital lock, mobile

  DynamicGameObject:
    Properties
      - type: GAME_OBJECT_TYPE
      - object: Pickable | Inspectable | MovableCover | Container

  InspectionData:
    Properties
      - appellation: string
      - information: string
    Usage guidelines:
      - The information field serves TWO distinct purposes:
        
        A) VISUAL DESCRIPTION (for objects with observable clues):
          - Describe what can be seen: numbers, symbols, positions, states
          - Examples: "A clock stopped at 02:41", "A calendar with March 15th circled in red"
          - Keep it concise (1-3 sentences)
          
        B) READABLE TEXT CONTENT (for documents, notes, letters):
          - Include the FULL text that is written on/in the item
          - Examples: diary entries (20-40 sentences), letters (10-20 sentences), notes (5-15 sentences)
          - The text must contain ALL clues needed for the puzzle, but NOT the solution directly
      
      - Information must NEVER:
        - Tell the player what to do
        - Explain how to solve the puzzle
        - State "this is a clue for X"
      
      - Information must ALWAYS:
        - Be complete enough that a careful reader can extract the necessary clue
        - Match the object type (visual for clocks/paintings, textual for letters/notebooks)

  ENUMs:
    SPRITE_RESOLUTION:
      - 1024x1024 // square object
      - 1536x1024 // wide object
      - 1024x1536 // tall object
    Usage guidelines:
      Use resolution to match orientation:
        - square object → 1024x1024
        - wide object → 1536x1024
        - tall object → 1024x1536

    GAME_OBJECT_TYPE:
      - PICKABLE
      - INSPECTABLE
      - CONTAINER
      - MOVALBE_COVER

    POSITION:
      - WT1, WT2, WT3   // wall top
      - W1,  W2,  W3    // wall middle
      - WB1, WB2, WB3   // wall bottom
      - F1, F2, F3      // floor
      Description of position enum:
        - Floor positions (F1-F3):
          - Small objects like backpack, rag, bucket, carboard box
          - Big objects like antique desk, fridge, book shelf, chest
          - When a big object is placed on the floor, WB and W with the same index can not be placed
        - Wall Top Positions (WT1-WT3)
          - Small objects like clock, calendar, ventilation opening etc.
        - Wall Center Positions (W1-W3)
          - When current wall has Exit W2 can not have game element
          - Small and big objects like painting, wall safe, book shelf, TV, etc.
        - Wall Bottom Positions (WB1-WB3)
          - When current wall has Exit W2 can not have game element
          - Small objects like ventilation opening
        - Indexing means the horizontal position of the wall/floor: 1 = left side, 2 = center, 3 = right side. 